[{"location":"lib/internals/#Internals","page":"Internals","title":"Internals","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lib/internals/#Modules","page":"Internals","title":"Modules","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lib/internals/","page":"Internals","title":"Internals","text":"HillRegions\nHillRegions.Internal","category":"page"},{"location":"lib/internals/#HillRegions","page":"Internals","title":"HillRegions","text":"A complementary package to add the recipe to Plots.jl for plotting Hill regions.\n\nLinks:\n\nRepository\nDocumentation\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"module"},{"location":"lib/internals/#HillRegions.Internal","page":"Internals","title":"HillRegions.Internal","text":"This module contains all inner parts of this package.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"module"},{"location":"lib/internals/#Types","page":"Internals","title":"Types","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lib/internals/","page":"Internals","title":"Internals","text":"Modules = [HillRegions.Internal]\nOrder = [:constant, :type]","category":"page"},{"location":"lib/internals/#HillRegions.Internal.M_TYPE","page":"Internals","title":"HillRegions.Internal.M_TYPE","text":"M_TYPE = Union{Rational{Int}, Float64}\n\nA default type for the μ arguments.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"lib/internals/#HillRegions.Internal.C_TYPE","page":"Internals","title":"HillRegions.Internal.C_TYPE","text":"C_TYPE = Float64\n\nA default type for the C arguments.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"lib/internals/#HillRegions.Internal.HillRegion","page":"Internals","title":"HillRegions.Internal.HillRegion","text":"HillRegion\n\nHill region, described by the lesser of the two masses of the resting bodies (μ) and the Jacobi constant (C).\n\nFields\n\nμ::M_TYPE: the lesser of the two masses of the resting bodies\nC::C_TYPE: the Jacobi constant\n\nConstructors\n\nHillRegion(; μ::M_TYPE, C::C_TYPE)\nHillRegion(C::C_TYPE; μ::M_TYPE)\nHillRegion(μ::M_TYPE; C::C_TYPE)\nHillRegion(μ::M_TYPE, C::C_TYPE)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"lib/internals/#HillRegions.Internal.MR_TYPE","page":"Internals","title":"HillRegions.Internal.MR_TYPE","text":"MR_TYPE = Float64\n\nA default Real type for the μ arguments.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"lib/internals/#Functions","page":"Internals","title":"Functions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lib/internals/","page":"Internals","title":"Internals","text":"Modules = [HillRegions.Internal]\nOrder = [:function]","category":"page"},{"location":"lib/internals/#HillRegions.Internal._V-Tuple{ImplicitEquations.OInterval,ImplicitEquations.OInterval,Union{Rational{Int64}, Float64}}","page":"Internals","title":"HillRegions.Internal._V","text":"_V(x::OInterval, y::OInterval, μ::M_TYPE) -> OInterval\n\nReturn the value on the zero-velocity surface given by the Jacobi constant:\n\nV(x y μ) = 2 μ  ρ_2(x y) + 2 (1 - μ)  ρ_1(x y) + μ ρ_2^2(x y) + (1 - μ) ρ_1^2(x y)\n\nArguments\n\nx::OInterval: the interval of coordinates of the third body on the abscissa\ny::OInterval: the interval of coordinates of the third body on the ordinate\nμ::M_TYPE: the mass (dimensionless) of the smaller of the two resting bodies\n\nReturns\n\nOInterval: the interval of values of the V function\n\nExample\n\nusing HillRegions\nusing ImplicitEquations\nusing IntervalArithmetic\n\nOInterval = HillRegions.Internal.OInterval\nTRUE = ImplicitEquations.BInterval(true, true)\n\nx = OInterval(Interval(-1., 1.), TRUE, TRUE)\ny = OInterval(Interval(1., 1.), TRUE, TRUE)\nμ = 1//11\n\nρ₁ = HillRegions.Internal._ρ₁\nρ₂ = HillRegions.Internal._ρ₂\n\n(HillRegions.Internal._V(x, y, μ) == 2 * μ / ρ₂(x, y, μ) + 2 * (1 - μ) / ρ₁(x, y, μ) +\n                                     μ * ρ₂(x, y, μ)^2 + (1 - μ) * ρ₁(x, y, μ)^2) == TRUE\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"lib/internals/#HillRegions.Internal._predicate-Tuple{HillRegion}","page":"Internals","title":"HillRegions.Internal._predicate","text":"_predicate(HR::HillRegion) -> ImplicitEquations.Pred\n\nReturn a predicate in the form of V = C where μ and C are from a HillRegion object.\n\nArguments\n\nHR::HillRegion: a Hill region\n\nReturns\n\nImplicitEquations.Pred: a predicate\n\nExample\n\nusing HillRegions\nusing ImplicitEquations\nusing IntervalArithmetic\n\nOInterval = HillRegions.Internal.OInterval\nTRUE = ImplicitEquations.BInterval(true, true)\n\nx = OInterval(Interval(-1., 1.), TRUE, TRUE)\ny = OInterval(Interval(1., 1.), TRUE, TRUE)\nμ = 1//11\nC = 3.0\n\npred = HillRegions.Internal._predicate(HillRegion(μ, C))\n(pred.f(x, y) == HillRegions.Internal._V(x, y, μ)) == TRUE\n\nSee also: _V, _ρ₁, _ρ₂\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"lib/internals/#HillRegions.Internal._ρ₁-Tuple{ImplicitEquations.OInterval,ImplicitEquations.OInterval,Union{Rational{Int64}, Float64}}","page":"Internals","title":"HillRegions.Internal._ρ₁","text":"_ρ₁(x::OInterval, y::OInterval, μ::M_TYPE) -> OInterval\n\nReturn the distance between the first and the third bodies:\n\nρ_1^2(x y μ) = (x + μ)^2 + y^2\n\nArguments\n\nx::OInterval: the interval of coordinates of the third body on the abscissa\ny::OInterval: the interval of coordinates of the third body on the ordinate\nμ::M_TYPE: the mass (dimensionless) of the smaller of the two resting bodies\n\nReturns\n\nOInterval: the interval of distances\n\nExample\n\nusing HillRegions\nusing ImplicitEquations\nusing IntervalArithmetic\n\nOInterval = HillRegions.Internal.OInterval\nTRUE = ImplicitEquations.BInterval(true, true)\n\nx = OInterval(Interval(-1., 1.), TRUE, TRUE)\ny = OInterval(Interval(1., 1.), TRUE, TRUE)\nμ = 1//11\n\n(HillRegions.Internal._ρ₁(x, y, μ) == √((x + μ)^2 + y^2)) == TRUE\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"lib/internals/#HillRegions.Internal._ρ₂-Tuple{ImplicitEquations.OInterval,ImplicitEquations.OInterval,Union{Rational{Int64}, Float64}}","page":"Internals","title":"HillRegions.Internal._ρ₂","text":"_ρ₂(x::OInterval, y::OInterval, μ::M_TYPE) -> OInterval\n\nReturn the distance between the second and the third bodies:\n\nρ_2^2(x y μ) = (x - 1 + μ)^2 + y^2\n\nArguments\n\nx::OInterval: the interval of coordinates of the third body on the abscissa\ny::OInterval: the interval of coordinates of the third body on the ordinate\nμ::M_TYPE: the mass (dimensionless) of the smaller of the two resting bodies\n\nReturns\n\nOInterval: the interval of distances\n\nExample\n\nusing HillRegions\nusing ImplicitEquations\nusing IntervalArithmetic\n\nOInterval = HillRegions.Internal.OInterval\nTRUE = ImplicitEquations.BInterval(true, true)\n\nx = OInterval(Interval(-1., 1.), TRUE, TRUE)\ny = OInterval(Interval(1., 1.), TRUE, TRUE)\nμ = 1//11\n\n(HillRegions.Internal._ρ₂(x, y, μ) == √((x - 1 + μ)^2 + y^2)) == TRUE\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"lib/#Package-Index","page":"Index","title":"Package Index","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lib/","page":"Index","title":"Index","text":"Pages = [\"internals.md\"]","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/guide/#Guide","page":"Guide","title":"Package Guide","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/guide/","page":"Guide","title":"Guide","text":"This package is for easy plotting of zero-velocity curves (aka Hill curves) for the general three-body problem. These curves become zero-velocity surfaces in three-dimensional space that bound a region called the Hill region. It is a region that the third body cannot leave. The problem is narrowed down to specifying the Jacobi constant and the lesser of the two masses of the resting bodies.","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/guide/#Installation","page":"Guide","title":"Installation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/guide/","page":"Guide","title":"Guide","text":"This package is an implementation of a learning assignment and solves a very narrow problem, so it is not available in the General registry. It will be available in the personal registry soon.","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/guide/#Plotting-Hill-curves","page":"Guide","title":"Plotting Hill curves","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/guide/","page":"Guide","title":"Guide","text":"This package provides a recipe for the Plots.jl package. It is necessary to create an instance of the HillRegion type to use it, specifying the lesser of the masses of two resting bodies (in the co-rotating system) and the Jacobi constant:","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/guide/","page":"Guide","title":"Guide","text":"using HillRegions\nHR = HillRegion(μ = 1//11, C = 3.652916)","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/guide/","page":"Guide","title":"Guide","text":"Now you can plot the Hill curves:","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/guide/","page":"Guide","title":"Guide","text":"using Plots\nENV[\"GKSwstype\"]=\"100\" # hide\nplot(HR, M=12, N=12)","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/guide/","page":"Guide","title":"Guide","text":"Crosses mark the positions of two resting bodies at coordinates -μ and 1 - μ.","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/guide/","page":"Guide","title":"Guide","text":"To find out more about the additional arguments provided by the recipe, check the Recipe page.","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/recipe/#Recipe","page":"Recipe","title":"Recipe","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/recipe/","page":"Recipe","title":"Recipe","text":"The recipe's function signature looks like this:","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/recipe/","page":"Recipe","title":"Recipe","text":"function f(\n    HR::HillRegion;\n    bodiesmarker=:x,\n    bodiescolor=colorant\"#425378\",\n    shapecolor=colorant\"#425378\",\n)","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/recipe/","page":"Recipe","title":"Recipe","text":"Keyword arguments:","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/recipe/","page":"Recipe","title":"Recipe","text":"bodiesmarker: the marker shape for displaying resting bodies\nbodiescolor: the color of the markers for resting bodies\nshapecolor: the Hill curves color","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/recipe/","page":"Recipe","title":"Recipe","text":"Note that this recipe inherits the recipe parameters from the ImplicitEquations.jl package, so those can be changed, too. In particular, the parameters M and N are responsible for the resolution when using the Tupper algorithm. See the source file for details.","category":"page"},{"location":"lib/public/#Public-Interface","page":"Public","title":"Public Interface","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"lib/public/","page":"Public","title":"Public","text":"This package provides a recipe for the Plots.jl package using the HillRegion type.","category":"page"},{"location":"#HillRegions.jl","page":"Home","title":"HillRegions.jl","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"A recipe to plot Hill regions.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"\n<table style=\"width: fit-content; border-collapse: collapse;\">\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <th style=\"text-align: center; border: 1px solid lightgray; padding: 6px 12px;\">\n        Code Coverage\n      </th>\n\n      <th style=\"text-align: center; border: 1px solid lightgray; padding: 6px 12px;\">\n        Repository & License\n      </th>\n\n      <th style=\"text-align: center; border: 1px solid lightgray; padding: 6px 12px;\">\n        Playground\n      </th>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td style=\"text-align: center; border: 1px solid lightgray; padding: 6px 12px;\">\n        <a href=\"https://codecov.io/gh/paveloom-j/HillRegions.jl\" style=\"position: relative; bottom: -2px;\">\n          <img src=\"https://codecov.io/gh/paveloom-j/HillRegions.jl/branch/master/graph/badge.svg\" />\n        </a>\n      </td>\n\n      <td style=\"text-align: center; border: 1px solid lightgray; padding: 6px 12px;\">\n        <a href=\"https://github.com/paveloom-j/HillRegions.jl\" style=\"position: relative; bottom: -2px;\">\n          <img src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/GitHub-paveloom--j%2FHillRegions.jl-5DA399.svg\">\n        </a>\n        <a href=\"https://github.com/paveloom-j/HillRegions.jl/blob/master/LICENSE.md\" style=\"position: relative; bottom: -2px;\">\n          <img src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/license-MIT-5DA399.svg\">\n        </a>\n      </td>\n\n      <td style=\"text-align: center; border: 1px solid lightgray; padding: 6px 12px;\">\n        <a href=\"https://mybinder.org/v2/gh/paveloom-j/HillRegions.jl/master?urlpath=lab/tree/playground.ipynb\" style=\"position: relative; bottom: -2px;\">\n          <img src=\"https://mybinder.org/badge_logo.svg\">\n        </a>\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"A complementary package to add the recipe to Plots.jl for plotting Hill regions.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Package-Features","page":"Home","title":"Package Features","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Plot Hill curves easily","category":"page"},{"location":"#Manual-Outline","page":"Home","title":"Manual Outline","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Pages = map(\n    s -> \"manual/$(s)\",\n    [\"guide.md\", \"recipe.md\"],\n)","category":"page"},{"location":"#Library-Outline","page":"Home","title":"Library Outline","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Pages = map(\n    s -> \"lib/$(s)\",\n    [\"index.md\", \"public.md\", \"internals.md\"],\n)","category":"page"}]
